# How You Must Work

## General Behavior
- Prefer clarity over cleverness in every solution you produce.
- Make small, focused changes. Address one concern per task.
- Before writing any code: think through the problem, state your approach, identify edge cases, and list every file you will touch. Wait for confirmation before proceeding.
- If you are unsure about intended behavior, ask. Do not infer and proceed.
- Never modify files outside the scope of the current task without explicit instruction.

## SOLID
- Give every class and function a single reason to change. If you need "and" to describe what something does, split it.
- Extend behavior through composition and dependency injection. Do not modify existing classes to add new behavior.
- Write subtypes that are fully substitutable for their base types. Use `Protocol` when only behavior matters, not shared state.
- Define narrow `Protocol` interfaces. Do not force callers to depend on methods they do not use.
- Make high-level modules depend on abstractions. Never instantiate concrete collaborators inside business logic — inject them.

## Type Hints
- Add type hints to every function signature and class attribute. No exceptions.
- Always declare return types explicitly, including `-> None`.
- Never use `Any` unless wrapping an untyped third-party boundary. When you must, add a comment explaining why.
- Use `TypeVar`, `Generic`, and `Protocol` for reusable abstractions.
- Prefer `X | None` over `Optional[X]`.
- Resolve all `mypy` strict mode errors. Never suppress them without a written explanation in the same line comment.

## Error Handling
- Never use bare `except:`. Always name the exception type.
- Never silently swallow exceptions. Always log or re-raise.
- Define domain-specific exception classes that carry context. Do not raise raw `ValueError` or `RuntimeError` from business logic.
- At service boundaries, use explicit error types rather than relying on exceptions for expected failure states.
- Wrap all external I/O (network, filesystem, database) in explicit error handling.

## Functions and Classes
- Keep functions focused on one thing. Question any function that exceeds ~30 lines.
- Never write functions with more than 4 positional parameters. Group related arguments into a dataclass or `TypedDict`.
- Never use mutable default arguments.
- Use `dataclasses` or `pydantic` models for structured data. Never pass raw dicts across boundaries.
- If a class has no state, use module-level functions instead.
- Avoid deep inheritance. Default to composition and protocols.

## Immutability and State
- Use `frozen=True` on dataclasses wherever the data should not change after creation.
- Treat shared mutable state as a design problem. Isolate it explicitly and flag it when you introduce it.
- Separate pure functions from functions with side effects. Label side-effectful functions clearly in their docstring.

## Imports
- Use absolute imports only.
- Order imports: stdlib → third-party → internal, with a blank line between each group.
- Never use star imports.
- Treat circular imports as a design error. Resolve them by restructuring, not by moving imports into function scope.

## Testing
- Always follow TDD: write the failing test first, then write the minimum code to make it pass, then refactor. Never write implementation code without a corresponding failing test already in place.
- Every test must be meaningful. Never write a test just to increase coverage. A test that does not verify real behavior is worse than no test — it creates false confidence.
- For every function or behavior, cover: the happy path, edge cases (empty input, boundary values, None), and failure paths (exceptions, invalid input, external errors). A test suite that only covers the happy path is incomplete.
- Structure every test as Arrange / Act / Assert with one logical assertion.
- Use `pytest` fixtures for setup. Do not use `setUp`/`tearDown` patterns.
- Mock at the boundary only — external I/O, network calls, third-party services. Never mock internal application logic.
- Name tests after behavior: `test_user_cannot_log_in_with_expired_token`, not `test_login_fail`.
- Parametrize edge cases instead of duplicating test bodies.
- Coverage is a signal, not a goal. 80%+ on business logic and 100% on critical paths (auth, payments, data integrity) — but only if those tests are meaningful.

## Documentation
- Add docstrings to all public functions, classes, and modules.
- Write docstrings that explain *why* and *what*, not *how*. The code explains how.
- Add inline comments to complex business logic that explain the reasoning, not the mechanics.
- Every `TODO` or `FIXME` must include a ticket or issue reference. Do not leave orphaned comments.

## Security
- Never log secrets, tokens, or PII.
- Never hardcode credentials. Use environment variables or a secrets manager.
- Validate and sanitize all external input before it reaches business logic.
- Always use parameterized queries. Never interpolate user input into query strings.
- Never introduce a new dependency without stating why the existing stack cannot solve the problem.

## Performance
- Write correct code first. Do not optimize preemptively.
- When asked to optimize, profile before changing anything and show the evidence.
- Identify and fix N+1 query patterns at the data access layer. Treat them as bugs.
- Put expensive operations (external calls, heavy computation) behind abstractions that can be cached or made async.

---

# Hard Limits
- Never reduce test coverage to make a task easier.
- Never suppress linter or type checker warnings without an explanatory comment on the same line.
- Never rename, restructure, or refactor code that is not directly related to the current task.
- Never add a dependency without justification.
- Never produce code you cannot walk through line by line if asked.

---

# Definition of Done
Before considering any task complete, run the following and verify all pass:
1. `pytest -x --tb=short` — all tests pass.
2. `mypy --strict .` — no type errors.
3. `black --check .` — no formatting violations.
4. `ruff check .` — no lint errors.
5. Any new `# type: ignore` or `# noqa` has an explanatory comment.
6. All new functionality has corresponding tests written before the implementation.
7. No files outside the task scope were modified.
